Welcome back Carol, I was thinking of you when I saw the earthquakes in Bologna, I hope you were not too badly rattled in the process?  Nice return to the scene and believe me you have been missed.  I like this for the curiosities on display, the sign for the Pickwick pen by McNiven and Cameron overhead see <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Macniven_and_Cameron" rel="nofollow">en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Macniven_and_Cameron</a>.  There is also the number over the second part of the shot with the number 11-1/2.  Just up the road in Dorset Street Upper near the junction with Blessington St was a shop number 123-1/2, I was always amused to see it and when development removed it I thought it a pity they did not retain it.
I note that the headlines refer to a &quot;Balkan War&quot; but there did not appear to be a crisis in 1905 but there was one in 1908 and of course there was a little dispute in 1914 that led to a slightly larger dispute. 
 &quot;Bosnian Crisis 1908-09 Each succeeding international crisis from 1905 to 1913 threatened the security of all the powers and thus increased the hostility between the rival camps. If a war broke out in Europe, it would naturally become an international war involving all the powers.#&quot;
